
[1]act

   ACT, v.i. [Gr., Lat. to urge, drive, lead, bring, do, perform, or in
   general to move, to exert force.]

   1. To exert power; as, the stomach acts upon food; the will acts upon
   the body in producing motion.

   2. To be in action or motion; to move

   He hangs between in doubt to act or rest.

   3. To behave, demean, or conduct, as in morals, private duties, or
   public offices; as, we know not why a minister has acted in this
   manner. But in this sense, it is most frequent in popular language; as,
   how the man acts or has acted.

   To act up to, is to equal in action; to fulfil or perform a
   correspondent action; as he has acted up to his engagement or his
   advantages.
